On Escalation Ticket # 00417173 the new comment has been added: Ethan Israel:

@Michael Burrofato @Sanjay Meghani @Salesforce @Helen Randall - 

Dev reviewed this, what the partner reproduced is not the same issue that TSMC is seeing. What the partner reproduced is related to the fact that the date range query in AIC queries all the events that fall into that range in GMT format, but then displays those events with the local timezone set on the AIC console, so it's not necessarily an issue that some events may fall slightly outside of the date range depending on the timezone of the AIC console. 

However, TSMC seems to be seeing an issue where activity events are multiple days past the applied filter, which would be a different. In order to diagnose that issue we'd really need the activity logs from TSMC containing the activity events from the date range in question. There's not really anything we can investigate without those logs. 

We'd also like to point out that it looks like TSMC is still on v11.0, which is no longer supported as of April 2024. So even if we were to identify a bug here we wouldn't be able to deliver a fix for 11.0. 

[DevOps CommentId:10821844]

On Escalation Ticket # 00417173 the new comment has been added: Ethan Israel:

@Salesforce @Helen Randall - Hey Pasan, 

The event in AIC is not showing in GMT timezone as far as we can tell. In the screenshot we got from TSMC ("Data not showing correctly in AIC.png") the date range selected is 8/1/2024-8/2/2024 using the local timezone (GMT+8), i uploaded a screenshot illustrating that the date range is using the local timezone (see "GMT plus 8.png" attached in SP). However, the activity events shown in the screenshot are showing an access time of 8/5/2024 which should also be using local timezone (GMT+8). So the issue is that we're seeing dates in local timezone outside of the selected date range, not that the events are shown in GMT. That's why we need TSMC's activity logs from NAM showing the actual full timestamp of the events, so we can determine when the events actually occurred and whether there's a date translation issue on the NAM side or AIC or somewhere else. 


I also want to reiterate that even if we do find a bug here we won't be able to deliver a fix for it in 11.0. 

[DevOps CommentId:10838634]
